<br>
<br>
I contacted him and told him I would help.  I used my locate corpse spell and found his corpse on top of the INN!! (no wonder he couldn't find it).  I guess he is a new player because he didn't know how to summon corpse.  I tried to tell him to type /corpse several times, but alas we could not communicate.  Finally, he managed to get lined up just right and loot his corpse while it was on the roof.  I tried to let him know through emotes that everything would work out, but I don't know if I was successful.  I wish there was a way I could have told him how to use the /corpse command since he was obviously new and extremely upset to see his corpse on the roof.  (sigh) <br>
<br>
Oh well, my good deed is taken care of for the next decade. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umaladominus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maladominus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/29/02 2:18:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1220.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Language problems</span><hr size=1> /agree Kayleth<br>
<br>
Sometimes I find it compelling to help another player (especially ones like newbies who dont know any better) even if it temporarily &quot;breaks&quot; role playing with me being an evil necromancer and the person in need being a goody-good. This is especially true if no one else is around or willing to help that poor person. A newbie in a desperate corpse run is something I give sympathy to, because they are in danger of losing everything they have. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   <br>
I guess he is a new player because he didn't know how to summon corpse. I tried to tell him to type /corpse several times, but alas we could not communicate. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Unfortunately, this is one of those examples where the language barrier really does get in the way of practical gameplay. There will be many desperate situations where you simply cannot communicate with another player because of our language barrier. <br>
<br>
For example, the other night I was in West Commonlands, and saw a Griffin heading towards an Erudite necromancer meditating on a hill a few yards away from me. I tried to warn him in advance. I only had a few seconds to warn him.... in my Gnomish tongue. Apparently most Erudites dont know a word of Gnomish. He probably thought I was just some babbling idiot. <br>
<br>
I say in Gnomish &quot;griffin coming, get up!&quot;<br>
<br>
I say in Gnomish &quot;griffin coming, get up!&quot;<br>
<br>
I say in Gnomish &quot;griffin coming, run!&quot; <br>
<br>
Well, eventually I had to run away.... and sure enough the Griffin plunged right into the medding Erudite spellcaster... and ate him alive in 2 or 3 hits. Dead Erudite. <br>
<br>
I wish I had switched to Human Tongue to warn him (since I learned it well enough from you, Average level). But in a panic situation I simply used my default racial language, which is Gnomish. Even had I used Human, I take it that not all Erudites are necessarilly fluent speakers of the Human language. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   <br>
Oh well, my good deed is taken care of for the next decade. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yep, you did good. <br>
<br>
P.S. - when's our next lesson? <br>
<br>
*giggle*<br>
<br>
Edit -- Kayleth, I wanted to make sure you know how much I appreciate you teaching me Human. I can finally talk to people! Now Humanity will never be the same, as they can now hear a little Gnome brag about his sexy bad self! <br>
<br>
/cheer Kayleth <br>
